  "text": "Proof: See Appendix F for the proof. We note that can be analytically derived for a given connectivity radius if the spatial distribution of the nodes is uniform [CITATION_1] . Proposition 5 implies that for a random geometric graph with max-degree weights should be chosen to satisfy . This result indicates that for highly connected graphs, which have a large value of , a small is desirable. For these graphs, standard consensus achieves fast mixing, so the prediction becomes less important and should be assigned less weight. In the case of a sparsely connected graph (small ), a large is desirable. For these graphs, the convergence of standard consensus is slow because there are few connections, so the prediction component of the accelerated algorithm should receive more weight.",
